## Notes / References Section

### Well-Being and Goals

- **William G. Bowen** and **Derek Curtis Bok**, *The Shape of the River: Long-Term Consequences of Considering Race in College and University Admissions* (Princeton UP, 1998) — study on goals young people set
- **Carol Nickerson**, **Norbert Schwarz**, and **Ed Diener**, "Financial Aspirations, Financial Success, and Overall Life Satisfaction: Who? and How?" *Journal of Happiness Studies* 8 (2007): 467–515

### Money and Well-Being

- *"being very well-off financially"* data: **Alexander Astin**, M. R. King, G. T. Richardson, "The American Freshman: National Norms for Fall 1976," Cooperative Institutional Research Program, UCLA, 1976
- *money was not important*: Kahneman, "Puzzles of Well-Being," presented at American Economic Association annual meeting, 2004

### Happiness of Californians

- Question of how well people today can forecast feelings of descendants 100 years from now is relevant to **climate change policy** — but can only be studied indirectly
- Key conceptual clarification: **Happiness ≠ Life satisfaction**
  - **Life satisfaction** = thoughts and feelings when reflecting on your life (e.g., in surveys)
  - **Happiness** = feelings people have as they live normal daily life
- Kahneman notes he was "guilty of a confusion" between these two concepts in earlier work

### California vs. Midwest Satisfaction

- **Asian students** reported lower life satisfaction generally
- Asian students made up a much larger share of California samples than Midwest samples
- When controlling for this difference, **life satisfaction in the two regions was identical** — the apparent California advantage disappears

### Car Ownership and Pleasure

- **Jing Xu** and **Norbert Schwarz**: quality of a car (by Blue Book value) predicts owners' answer to a general question about car satisfaction — (continues on next page)

<!-- p. 555 -->

## Notes & References — Part V / Conclusions

### Hedonic Experience & Commuting
- Car quality predicts enjoyment during **joyrides** but has **no effect on mood during normal commutes**
- Source: **Norbert Schwarz**, **Daniel Kahneman**, and **Jing Xu**, "Global and Episodic Reports of Hedonic Experience," in *Using Calendar and Diary Methods in Life Events Research* (Sage), pp. 157–74

### Paraplegics & Mood
- Study on whether paraplegics spend time in bad moods — described in detail in Kahneman, "Evaluation by Moments"
- Source on coping with irrevocable loss: **Camille Wortman** and **Roxane C. Silver**, "Coping with Irrevocable Loss, Cataclysms, Crises, and Catastrophes," APA Master Lecture Series 6 (1987): 189–235

### Colostomy Patients & Memory Bias
- **Dylan Smith et al.** — "Misremembering Colostomies? Former Patients Give Lower Utility Ratings than Do Current Patients," *Health Psychology* 25 (2006): 688–95
- Former patients remember their experience worse than current patients rate it — classic **peak-end** / **memory vs. experience** divergence
- Also: **Loewenstein** and **Ubel**, "Hedonic Adaptation and the Role of Decision and Experience Utility in Public Policy," *Journal of Public Economics* 92 (2008): 1795–1810

### Miswanting
- Term **"miswanting"** coined by **Daniel Gilbert** and **Timothy D. Wilson**
- Source: "Miswanting: Some Problems in Affective Forecasting," in *Feeling and Thinking: The Role of Affect in Social Cognition*, ed. Joseph P. Forgas (Cambridge UP, 2000), 178–97

---

## Conclusions (opening references)

### Utility & Health Valuation
- **Paul Dolan** and **Daniel Kahneman**, "Interpretations of Utility and Their Implications for the Valuation of Health," *Economic Journal* 118 (2008): 215–234
- **Loewenstein** and **Ubel**, "Hedonic Adaptation and the Role of Decision and Experience Utility in Public Policy"

### Well-Being & Government Policy
- Progress on **well-being measurement** as official policy has been especially rapid in the **UK**
- Driven in large part by **Lord Richard Layard**'s *Happiness: Lessons from a New Science* (2005)
- Layard among prominent economists/social scientists drawn into well-being research
- Other key sources named: **Derek Bok**, *The Politics of Happiness: What...* (continues on next page)

<!-- p. 556 -->

## Notes / Bibliography (continued)

### Well-Being & Public Policy References

- **Ed Diener**, Richard Lucus, Ulrich Schmimmack, and John F. Helliwell, *Well-Being for Public Policy* (Oxford University Press, 2009)
- **Alan B. Krueger**, ed., *Measuring the Subjective Well-Being of Nations: National Account of Time Use and Well-Being* (U of Chicago Press, 2009)
- **Joseph E. Stiglitz**, **Amartya Sen**, and Jean-Paul Fitoussi, *Report of the Commission on the Measurement of Economic Performance and Social Progress*
- Paul Dolan, Richard Layard, and Robert Metcalfe, *Measuring Subjective Well-being for Public Policy: Recommendations on Measures* (Office for National Statistics, 2011)

### On "Irrational" as a Term

- Kahneman notes that **"irrational" is a strong word** — his view of the mind is not much different from **Dan Ariely**'s in *Predictably Irrational: The Hidden Forces That Shape Our Decisions* (Harper, 2008), but they differ in use of the term

### Rational Addiction

- **Gary S. Becker** and **Kevin M. Murphy**, "A Theory of Rational Addiction," *Journal of Political Economics* 96 (1988): 675–700
- **Richard H. Thaler** and **Cass R. Sunstein**, *Nudge: Improving Decisions About Health, Wealth, and Happiness* (Yale University Press, 2008)

### Checklists & Organizational Decision-Making

- **Atul Gawande**, *The Checklist Manifesto: How to Get Things Right* (Holt, 2009)
- **Daniel Kahneman**, Dan Lovallo, and Oliver Sibony, "The Big Idea: Before You Make That Big Decision…" *Harvard Business Review* 89 (2011): 50–60

### Cognitive Repairs / Organizational Practices

- **Chip Heath**, Richard P. Larrick, and Joshua Klayman, "Cognitive Repairs: How Organizational Practices Can Compensate for Individual Shortcomings," *Research in Organizational Behavior* 20 (1998): 1–37
- Key idea: **organizations can institutionalize procedures** that correct for individual cognitive biases even when individuals cannot correct themselves

