## Notes: Key Source Annotations by Chapter

*(These are the author's own annotations clarifying claims in
the text — more useful than a standard bibliography.)*

### Introduction

- **Small sample sizes in psychology**: Jacob Cohen,
  *Statistical Power Analysis for the Behavioral Sciences* (1969)
  — the book Kahneman and Tversky had read that criticized
  psychologists for using small samples
- **Cognitive illusions critic**: **Gerd Gigerenzer** (German
  psychologist) was the most persistent critic of K&T's
  "negative view of the mind" framing
  - Key rebuttal: Kahneman and Tversky, "On the Reality of
    Cognitive Illusions," *Psychological Review* 103 (1996)
- **Nobel Prize**: Formally named the Bank of Sweden Prize in
  Economic Sciences in Memory of Alfred Nobel; first given 1969;
  some physical scientists opposed adding a social science prize
- **System 1/System 2 terminology**: Borrowed from
  **Keith Stanovich** and **Richard West** —
  "Individual Differences in Reasoning: Implications for the
  Rationality Debate," *Behavioral and Brain Sciences* (2000)
- **Affect heuristic**: Developed by **Paul Slovic**,
  classmate of Amos Tversky's at Michigan

### Ch. 2: Attention and Effort

- Core material draws on Kahneman's own *Attention and Effort*
  (1973) — thesis: attention is a **limited general resource**
- **Pupil dilation** as effort measure: Eckhard Hess,
  "Attitude and Pupil Size," *Scientific American* (1965)
- **Law of least effort**: Wouter Kool et al., "Decision Making
  and the Avoidance of Cognitive Demand" (2010)
- Brain region that assesses overall value of an action treats
  **effort invested as a cost** in the neural computation
  (McGuire & Botvinick, PNAS 2010)
- High SAT scorers show **smaller pupillary dilations** than low
  scorers on identical tasks — more intelligent brains use
  less effort to solve the same problems (Ahern & Beatty, 1979)

### Ch. 3: The Lazy Controller

- **"Optimal experience" / flow**: Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi,
  *Flow: The Psychology of Optimal Experience* (1990)
- **Ego depletion** (glucose as mechanism): Gailliot et al.,
  "Self-Control Relies on Glucose as a Limited Energy Source,"
  *JPSP* (2007) — "willpower is more than a mere metaphor"
- **Depletion in judicial decisions**: Shai Danziger et al.,
  "Extraneous Factors in Judicial Decisions," *PNAS* (2011) —
  the Israeli parole board study
- **Cognitive Reflection Test**: Shane Frederick (2005) —
  the bat-and-ball style questions; high scorers are more
  rational and less susceptible to heuristics-and-biases tasks
- **Marshmallow test / delay of gratification**:
  **Walter Mischel** and Ebbe Ebbesen (1970); followed up in
  Science (1989) — children who waited longer scored higher on
  SAT and intelligence tests decades later
- **Stanovich** framing: high CRT scorers are "more rational"
  per *Rationality and the Reflective Mind* (2011)

### Ch. 4: The Associative Machine

- **Associative processes in intuitive judgment**:
  Morewedge & Kahneman, *Trends in Cognitive Sciences* (2010)
- **Embodied cognition** ("think with your body"):
  Paula Niedenthal, "Embodying Emotion," *Science* (2007)
- **Elderly walking priming**: John Bargh et al. (1996) —
  words related to old age activate stereotype, slow walking
- **Facial feedback hypothesis**: Strack, Martin & Stepper (1988) —
  holding pencil in teeth (forced smile) increases humor ratings
- **Voting location priming**: Jonah Berger et al., "Contextual
  Priming: Where People Vote Affects How They Vote," *PNAS* (2008)
- **Money priming** reduces helpfulness and increases
  self-reliance: Kathleen Vohs, *Science* (2006)
- **Lady Macbeth effect**: Chen-Bo Zhong & Liljenquist (2006) —
  moral threat triggers desire for physical cleansing; specific
  to the motor modality involved in transgression (hand vs. mouth)
- **Eye-watching cooperative behavior**: Bateson, Nettle, Roberts
  (2006) — images of watching eyes at a British university
  increased contributions to an honesty box

### Ch. 5: Cognitive Ease

- Technical term for cognitive ease: **fluency**
- **Processing difficulty → analytic mode**: Alter, Oppenheimer
  et al. (2007) — hard-to-read fonts trigger System 2 engagement
- **Stocks with fluent names outperform** on IPO day:
  Alter & Oppenheimer, *PNAS* (2006); Cooper et al. (2001)
  — easy ticker symbols also predict short-term performance
- **Mere exposure effect**: Robert Zajonc (1968) — repeated
  exposure to a stimulus increases liking even without
  conscious recognition; works subliminally (Monahan et al. 2000)
- **Rhyming aphorisms judged more true**: McG lone &
  Tofighbakhsh (2000)
- **Familiarity feeling**: operates as a fallback when specific
  memories are unavailable — protects from acting astonished
  at someone who only looks vaguely familiar
- **Positive mood doubles accuracy** on coherence intuition tasks:
  Bolte, Goschke & Kuhl (2003)
- Cognitive ease forms a cluster with: good mood, increased
  credulity, reduced vigilance, reliance on intuition

### Ch. 6: Norms, Surprises, and Causes

- **Norm Theory**: Kahneman & Dale Miller (1986) —
  reality compared to automatically generated alternatives
- Infants as young as **six months perceive causality**:
  Leslie & Keeble (1987)
- Humans are "teleologically obsessed" — we see purpose and
  agent causation everywhere, even in abstract shapes
  (Heider & Simmel, 1944 — triangles and circles appear to
  have intentions)

### Ch. 7: A Machine for Jumping to Conclusions

- **Unbelieving the unbelievable**: Daniel Gilbert et al. (1990) —
  people initially believe statements before evaluating them;
  cognitive busyness prevents unbelieving
- **Solomon Asch** (1946): first impressions from adjective lists;
  order matters — "intelligent, industrious, impulsive…" vs.
  reversed order yields different personality impressions
- **Wisdom of Crowds**: James Surowiecki (2005)

### Ch. 8: How Judgments Happen

- **Face trustworthiness judgments**: Alexander Todorov et al. —
  competence inferred from faces predicts election outcomes
  (*Science* 2005); judgments made in 100 milliseconds
  (*Journal of Nonverbal Behavior* 2010)
- Less-informed voters (watch less television) rely more on
  facial appearance when voting (Lenz & Lawson)

### Ch. 9: Answering an Easier Question

- **Gigerenzer's "fast and frugal" heuristics** are different
  from Kahneman/Tversky heuristics: Gigerenzer emphasizes
  accuracy; K&T emphasize the biases heuristics produce
  - K&T critique: evidence for psychological reality of
    fast-and-frugal heuristics "remains thin and contested"
  - **Recognition heuristic** example: if you recognize one
    of two cities, guess it's larger — works if you know
    it's large; fails if you know it's small
  - Subjects actually use **more** information than just
    recognition (Oppenheimer, *Cognition* 2003)
  - Skill = ability to handle large amounts of information
    quickly, not to ignore information
- **Life satisfaction substitution**: correlation between
  "how happy are you?" and "how many dates last month?"
  was .66 when date question came first (Strack et al. 1988)
- Weather affects happiness self-reports in phone surveys
  unless respondents are first asked about the weather
  (anchoring attention on a non-representative factor)

<!-- pp. 521-540 -->

## Notes Section: Chapters 10–27 (Endnotes & Author Commentary)

> These pages are from the endnotes. Citations are omitted; only
> Kahneman's substantive clarifying remarks are captured below.

---

### Chapter 10: The Law of Small Numbers

- **Howard Wainer & Harris Zwerling** on small schools: smaller schools
  appear in both the best *and* worst lists — a statistical artifact
  of small sample variance, not a real effect
- **Jacob Cohen** (1962): estimated ~50% of social psychology studies
  were underpowered — a systemic problem predating replication crisis
- Original Tversky-Kahneman paper on **"Belief in the Law of Small
  Numbers"** (1971) used "intuition" broadly — not yet the
  System 1/System 2 vocabulary; any non-computational conclusion
  counted as "intuition"
- **William Feller** (*Introduction to Probability Theory*): used
  German spy bombing data to illustrate clustering in random sequences
- **Thomas Gilovich, Robert Vallone, Amos Tversky** (1985): the
  **"hot hand" fallacy** — basketball streaks are misperceptions of
  random sequences

---

### Chapter 11: Anchors

- **Robyn Le Boeuf & Eldar Shafir**: physical anchoring (e.g. body
  posture while estimating) — a "reasonable volume" study
- **Nicholas Epley & Thomas Gilovich**: self-generated anchors show
  *insufficient adjustment* — people stop adjusting when they reach
  a plausible value, not the correct one; experimenter-provided
  anchors work differently via **associative coherence**
- **Thomas Mussweiler**: anchoring activates category/exemplar
  knowledge consistent with the anchor value
- **Jacowitz & Kahneman** (1995): San Francisco Exploratorium study —
  measured anchoring quantitatively in estimation tasks
- **Northcraft & Neale** (real estate experts): high anchor was 12%
  above listed price, low anchor 12% below — experts' appraisals
  shifted substantially, contrary to their own belief
- **Englich, Mussweiler & Strack**: judges who rolled a pair of dice
  (rigged high or low) gave correspondingly longer/shorter sentences —
  irrelevant anchors affect expert judicial decisions
- **Brian Wansink et al.**: "NO LIMIT PER PERSON" signs increased
  purchase quantities — arbitrary number anchors purchasing behavior
- **Galinsky & Mussweiler**: first offers in negotiation act as
  anchors; perspective-taking helps resist the effect
- **Pogarsky & Babcock**: damage caps in litigation create anchors
  that paradoxically *increase* some awards (motivated anchoring)
- **Guthrie, Rachlinski & Wistrich**: judges exhibit anchoring
  as a cognitive illusion in judicial decision-making

---

### Chapter 12: The Science of Availability

- **Tversky & Kahneman** (1973): original availability paper —
  "ease with which" examples come to mind used as proxy for frequency
- **Ross & Sicoly** (1979): **egocentric bias** — spouses each
  claim more than half the shared work because their own contributions
  are more available to memory
- **Schwarz et al.**: major advance — showed it's the *ease* of
  retrieval, not the *content*, that serves as the heuristic signal
- **Sabine Stepper & Fritz Strack**: role of **fluency** — even
  proprioceptive cues affect emotional and nonemotional judgments
- Key moderators of ease-of-retrieval reliance:
  - Cognitively busy (effortful task concurrent) → rely less on ease
  - Happy mood → rely more on ease
  - Depressed → rely less on ease-of-retrieval
  - **Knowledgeable novices** rely on ease; **true experts** do not
  - High **faith in intuition** → rely more on ease
  - **Powerful people** rely more on ease of retrieval
    (Weick & Guinote, 2008)

---

### Chapter 13: Availability, Emotion, and Risk

- **Antonio Damasio**: "somatic marker hypothesis" — brain-damaged
  patients who can't feel emotion make poor decisions; emotion is
  integral to rational choice (*Descartes' Error*, 1994)
- **Paul Slovic** and colleagues: the **affect heuristic** — good
  feelings about a technology reduce perceived risk *and* increase
  perceived benefit; bad feelings do the reverse
  - Key finding: risk and benefit judgments are *negatively* correlated
    in laypeople (opposite of reality, where costly solutions
    are often the most beneficial)
- **Jonathan Haidt** (2001): "emotional dog and its rational tail" —
  moral judgments driven by emotion, rationalizations follow
- **Paul Slovic** (*The Perception of Risk*): "'Risk' does not exist
  in the world" — risk is a social construction shaped by affect
- **Timur Kuran & Cass Sunstein**: **availability cascade** — media
  attention → public fear → regulatory response, regardless of
  actual risk magnitude
- **CERCLA** (Superfund, 1980): example of availability cascade
  driving major legislation
- Alar apple scare: **60 Minutes** broadcast claiming 4,000 children
  would die of cancer — Slovic argues the public response was
  rational given EPA's demonstrated incompetence and the broadcast's
  imagery, not purely an availability distortion

---

### Chapter 14: Tom W's Specialty

- **Bayes's rule** (explained): posterior odds = prior odds ×
  likelihood ratio
  - Example: disease with 1/600 base rate, test with 25:1 likelihood
    ratio → positive test raises odds from 1/600 to 25/600 →
    probability only 4%, not the ~96% most people intuit
  - Tom W example: base rate 3% computer scientists → with likelihood
    ratio of 4, posterior probability rises to only ~11%
- **Jonathan Evans** (1984): heuristic vs. analytic processes in
  reasoning — representativeness dominates when base rates
  are not made salient
- **Norbert Schwarz et al.** (1991): when base rates are framed as
  *conversationally relevant*, people do use them — context matters
- **Alter, Oppenheimer, Epley & Eyre**: frowning (cognitive strain)
  improves base-rate usage — System 2 engagement helps

---

### Chapter 15: Linda: Less is More

- **Tversky & Kahneman** (1983): original **conjunction fallacy**
  paper — "Linda is a bank teller AND active in the feminist movement"
  judged more probable than "Linda is a bank teller"
- **Stephen Jay Gould**: acknowledged his own "little homunculus"
  kept insisting the conjunction was more probable even after
  understanding the logic (*Bully for Brontosaurus*)
- **Hertwig & Gigerenzer**: argued conjunction fallacy reflects
  intelligent inferences about conversational meaning, not pure error
  — the word "and" is ambiguous
- Resolution via **adversarial collaboration** (Mellers, Hertwig,
  Kahneman, 2001): frequency representations reduce conjunction
  effects but do not eliminate them; both sides partially correct

---

### Chapter 16: Causes Trump Statistics

- **Blue cab / Green cab problem**: correct Bayesian answer is 41%
  - Posterior odds = (.15/.85) × (.80/.20) = .706
  - Probability (Blue) = .706 / 1.706 = .41
- **Tversky & Kahneman** (1980): causal base rates (one cab company
  has bad accident record) are used; **"pallid" statistical base
  rates** are neglected
- **Nisbett & Borgida** (1975): University of Michigan study —
  vivid individual cases trump statistical summaries
- **Darley & Latané** (1968): diffusion of responsibility in
  emergencies — knowing others are present reduces individual
  intervention; people feel "relieved of responsibility"

---

### Chapter 17: Regression to the Mean

- **Francis Galton**: discovered regression to the mean; needed
  correlation theory to understand it — worked out the math himself
- **Standard scores**: transform raw scores by subtracting mean and
  dividing by standard deviation; regression coefficient equals
  correlation in standard-score form
- When correlation between parent and child height is high:
  regression to mean is weak; in malnourished populations,
  nutrition variance reduces the correlation
- **Jason Zweig** (personal communication): regression to the mean
  systematically distorts CEO recruitment — struggling firms hire
  from high-performing companies; new CEO gets credit for regression;
  replacement at old firm gets blame for the same regression going
  the other way → tens of millions in compensation awarded for
  what is statistically predictable mean reversion

---

### Chapter 18: Taming Intuitive Predictions

- Standard regression as optimal prediction assumes errors weighted
  by **squared deviation** (least-squares criterion)
- Regression toward the mean IS the mathematically correct
  prediction under this criterion — not a bias correction but the
  optimal solution

---

### Chapter 19: The Illusion of Understanding

- **Nassim Nicholas Taleb**: **narrative fallacy** (*The Black Swan*)
  — we construct tidy stories from random events
- **Michael Lewis** (*Moneyball*): scouts substituted vivid
  impressions for statistical prediction in baseball
- **Excite passed up buying Google for $750,000 in 1999** — a
  vivid case of narrative constructing false confidence
- **Nisbett & Wilson** (1977): people confabulate explanations for
  their own mental processes — introspection is unreliable
- **Fischhoff & Beyth** (1975): **hindsight bias** — after knowing
  outcomes, people dramatically revise their prior probability
  estimates upward ("I knew it all along")
- **Baron & Hershey** (1988): **outcome bias** — decisions judged
  by outcomes, not quality of reasoning at the time
- **Kamin & Rachlinski** (1995): hindsight bias distorts legal
  liability judgments
- **Philip Tetlock** (*Expert Political Judgment*, 2005): experts in
  high-stakes forecasting barely beat chance; self-described
  "hedgehogs" (one big idea) worse than "foxes"
- **Phil Rosenzweig** (*The Halo Effect*): business success stories
  (e.g., *In Search of Excellence*, *Built to Last*) suffer from
  halo effect — perceived success colors all other attributes
  - "Most Admired Companies" stocks do not outperform despised ones
- **Insider trading research**: even CEOs trading their own stock
  outperform by barely enough to cover trading costs —
  informational edge vastly overstated

---

### Chapter 20: The Illusion of Validity

- **Brad Barber & Terrance Odean**:
  - Individual investors who trade most earn least ("Trading Is
    Hazardous to Your Wealth")
  - Men trade more than women, underperform more ("Boys Will Be Boys")
  - **Disposition effect**: investors sell winners and hold losers
  - Taiwan study: wealth transfer from individuals to institutions
    = 2.2% of GDP annually
- **John Bogle**: mutual funds underperform the market net of fees
  — consistent with no persistent skill
- **Mark Grinblatt & Sheridan Titman** (1992): some evidence of
  persistent mutual fund performance — contested
- **Philip Tetlock** (*Expert Political Judgment*): in age of
  academic hyperspecialization, experts still fail at prediction

---

### Chapter 21: Intuitions vs. Formulas

- **Paul Meehl**: "There is no controversy" — actuarial (formula)
  prediction beats clinical (intuitive) prediction across domains;
  his "disturbing little book" was widely ignored for decades
- Wine pricing: formula using weather variables predicted 1960
  Chateau Latour price ($464/case) vs. 1961 ($5,432) — a factor of
  10+; the formula outperformed expert tasters
- **Experienced radiologists** are inconsistent with themselves when
  shown same X-rays twice — inter-rater and intra-rater reliability
  both low
- **James Shanteau** (1988): 41 studies — actuarial models beat
  experts in clinical psychology, medicine, auditing; experts
  retain edge mainly in domains with rapid, clear feedback
- **Israeli judge food-break study**: probability of parole =
  ~65% right after food break → drops to near 0% just before
  — irrelevant physiological factors dominate
- Unstructured interviews **lower** medical school admission validity
  vs. grades + scores alone (**Robyn Dawes** — "Belief in the
  Unstructured Interview")
- **Dr. Virginia Apgar**: Apgar score — simple checklist for newborn
  health — saved lives by replacing inconsistent clinical impressions
- **Atul Gawande** (*The Checklist Manifesto*): checklists as
  antidotes to expert inconsistency

### Chapter 22 (partial — "2{ce" heading, likely Ch. 22)

- **Getty Museum kouros**: world's leading Greek sculpture experts
  each felt immediate "intuitive repulsion" — sensed the statue
  (which passed scientific tests) was a modern fake; could not
  articulate why; one said "fresh," another said fingernails seemed
  wrong. Classic case of **valid expert intuition** that outran
  conscious reasoning
- **Herbert Simon**: "nothing less than recognition" — expert
  intuition is pattern recognition, not magic; a chess master "sees"
  the right move because position matches stored patterns
- The Getty case is suspicious precisely because experts agreed on
  the conclusion but could not agree on *why* — shared conclusion
  without shared reason is a warning sign, not validation
- **Simon**: Nobel laureate, pioneer of AI and cognitive science,
  bounded rationality; described intuition as "knowing without
  knowing how you know"
- **10,000 hours** of deliberate practice (Foer, *Moonwalking with
  Einstein*): prerequisite for genuine pattern-recognition expertise

---

### Chapter 23: The Outside View

- **"Inside view" vs. "outside view"**: widely misunderstood as
  "insider" vs. "outsider" — the distinction is between focusing
  on the specific case's details vs. the reference class of
  similar cases
- **Kahneman & Lovallo** (1993): **planning fallacy** — forecasts
  that are overly optimistic even when forecasters *know* the
  outside-view statistics
- **Richard Nisbett & Lee Ross** (*Human Inference*): "pallid"
  statistical information fails to engage intuition the way vivid
  case descriptions do
- **Scottish Parliament building**: originally estimated £40M;
  final cost ~£431M — canonical planning fallacy case
- **Brent Flyvbjerg**: public works projects systematically
  over-promise and under-deliver; exposure to outside-view data
  did NOT make planners more accurate (optimism is motivated)
- Survey: 90% of American homeowners believe their renovation will
  come in at or under budget — the outside view says most will not
- **Sunk-cost fallacy** (**Arkes & Blumer**, 1985): people continue
  failing projects because of prior investment — irrational but
  pervasive; humans more susceptible than lower animals

---

### Chapter 24: The Engine of Capitalism

- Optimism is partly genetic (twin studies, **Mosing et al.**) and
  partly linked to serotonin transporter gene
- **"Triumph of hope over experience"** (Puri & Robinson, 2007):
  optimistic entrepreneurs make more optimistic financial decisions
  across the board
- Entrepreneurs are **more sanguine than midlevel managers** in
  large organizations — selection and self-reinforcement
- **81% of entrepreneurs** estimated their chance of failure was
  zero (Cooper, Woo & Dunkelberg, 1988) — wildly inconsistent
  with ~35% 5-year survival rate for new businesses
- **Thomas Astebro**: independent inventors receive average return
  of 7 cents on the dollar — widespread, stubborn, costly optimism
- **"Hubris hypothesis"** (Richard Roll, 1986): M&A acquirers
  overpay because of CEO hubris — early behavioral finance paper
  predating the field
- **Malmendier & Tate**: overconfident CEOs do more value-destroying
  acquisitions and engage in earnings management ("Superstar CEOs")
- **Competition neglect** (eBay auction timing): sellers optimize
  for "most bidders online" (7pm EST) rather than "fewest competing
  auctions" (noon) — systematic failure to consider rivals
- **"Premortem" / diagnosis antemortem**: overconfidence in medicine
  is a leading cause of diagnostic error

---

### Chapter 25: Bernoulli's Errors

- **Weber's law**: sensitivity to stimuli is proportional —
  psychophysics underpins Bernoulli's logarithmic utility function
- Bernoulli's log-utility holds empirically: **Angus Deaton** found
  life satisfaction vs. log(GDP per capita) is nearly linear —
  doubling income yields roughly equal satisfaction increments
  regardless of initial wealth
- **St. Petersburg paradox** (Nicholas Bernoulli): infinite expected
  value game nobody would pay more than a few dollars for —
  explained by diminishing marginal utility of wealth
- Bernoulli's model survived because: (1) economists focused on
  choices between gains, not losses; (2) thinking in final
  wealth states is often reasonable; (3) it suited rational-choice
  modeling goals

---

### Chapter 26: Prospect Theory

- **Loss aversion ratio** typically 1.5–2.5 (Novemsky & Kahneman,
  2005)
- **Rabin's theorem**: if an agent rejects a 50/50 gamble to win
  $11 or lose $10 at *any* wealth level, Bernoulli's concave
  utility function implies absurd risk aversion for large stakes
  — mathematically proves expected utility theory cannot explain
  modest-stakes risk aversion without catastrophic implications
  for large-stakes choices
- Kahneman: discussing Rabin's proof to economist **Burton Malkiel**'s
  class changed attitudes — mathematical proofs carry authority
  that intuitive arguments don't

---

### Chapter 27: The Endowment Effect

- **Loss aversion in riskless choice**: kink in indifference curve
  at reference point — **Tversky & Kahneman** (1991);
  experimentally verified by **Jack Knetsch**
- **Alan Krueger** Super Bowl ticket study: 94% of lottery-winning
  fans would not buy at $3,000; 92% would not sell at $3,000 —
  buying price and selling price radically different for the same
  good; "rationality was in short supply at the Super Bowl"
- Token trading experiment logic: if half the tokens are randomly
  allocated, exactly half should trade (high-value holders without
  tokens buy from low-value holders with tokens) — in practice
  far fewer trades occur than theory predicts
- **Brain recordings** (Brian Knutson et al., 2008): neural
  antecedents of endowment effect visible in anticipatory affect
  circuits
- Loss aversion ratio from 100+ years of international price-of-risk
  data ≈ 2.3, consistent with lab experiments (**Moshe Levy**, 2010)
- **Housing market** (Genesove & Mayer, 2001): condo sellers in
  Boston set prices above market to avoid realizing a nominal loss —
  endowment effect in real estate
- **John List**: trading experience in markets reduces endowment
  effect — repeated market exposure trains away some loss aversion

<!-- pp. 541-560 -->

## Notes & References Section (Chapters 28–38 + Conclusions + Index)

*These pages are the endnotes/references section. Substantive
commentary is embedded within citations — captured below by chapter.*

---

## Chapter 31: Risk Policies — Notes

- **Myopic loss aversion**: treating each gamble separately
  rather than as part of a policy leads to worse decisions
  (Langer & Weber, *Journal of Economic Behavior* 2005)
- Combining a sure thing with a gamble: the math shows that
  broad framing (policy view) dominates narrow framing in
  expected value — the "inferior option BC" calculation is
  straightforward once both options are seen together

---

## Chapter 37: Experienced Well-Being — Notes

- **Cantril Self-Anchoring Striving Scale**: 0–10 ladder,
  "worst possible life" to "best possible life"
  - GDP and average ladder score correlate at r = .84
    across countries (Angus Deaton, *Journal of Economic
    Perspectives* 2008) — people share a common standard
    for a good life
- **Day Reconstruction Method** (Kahneman et al., *Science*
  2004): reconstructs moment-to-moment experience from
  diary; reveals how time is actually spent emotionally
- **Ecological Momentary Assessment**: continuous heart rate,
  blood pressure, saliva sampling alongside mood reports
- **U-index**: fraction of time spent in unpleasant states —
  proposed as welfare measure (Krueger, ed., 2009)
- Income and well-being split:
  - **Kahneman & Angus Deaton** (*PNAS* 2010, n > 450,000):
    higher income improves **life evaluation** but not
    **emotional well-being** beyond ~$75,000/year
  - Effect of income on happiness is *worse for the very
    poor* — financial resources buffer impact of disability
    (Smith et al., *Psychological Science* 2005)

---

## Chapter 38: Thinking About Life — Notes

### Focusing Illusion
- **Norbert Schwarz & Fritz Strack**: life satisfaction
  ratings heavily influenced by transient mood — a dime on
  a copying machine raised reported life satisfaction
- Car quality (Blue Book value) predicts happiness during
  joyrides but has **no effect on mood during commutes** —
  object only matters when attended to
- **Californians vs. Midwesterners**: no actual difference
  in life satisfaction once Asian student composition
  controlled for — the focusing illusion inflates the
  perceived effect of climate on happiness

### Affective Forecasting
- **Daniel Gilbert & Timothy Wilson**: "affective forecasting"
  — people systematically mispredict their future emotional
  states; focusing illusion drives miswanting
- **Miswanting** (Gilbert & Wilson, 2000): wanting things
  that won't make you happy because you focus on them
  when imagining the future

### Goals & Aspirations
- Young people who set financial goals as primary life
  aspiration reported lower life satisfaction than peers —
  even when they achieved those goals (Nickerson, Schwarz,
  Diener, *Journal of Happiness Studies* 2007)
- **Happiness ≠ life satisfaction**: Kahneman clarifies —
  life satisfaction is thoughts about your life
  (occurs occasionally, including during surveys);
  happiness is feelings during normal daily life

---

## Conclusions — Notes

- **Experienced utility** vs. **decision utility** distinction
  is "too important to be ignored" for health policy
  (Dolan & Kahneman, *Economic Journal* 2008)
- UK has made well-being measurement **official government
  policy** — driven by **Lord Richard Layard**'s
  *Happiness: Lessons from a New Science* (2005)
- Key policy thinkers: **Derek Bok**, **Joseph Stiglitz**,
  **Amartya Sen**, **Jean-Paul Fitoussi** (Commission on
  Measurement of Economic Performance and Social Progress)
- **Dan Ariely**'s *Predictably Irrational*: Kahneman notes
  their views of the mind are similar but they differ on
  use of the word "irrational"
- **Nudge** (Thaler & Sunstein, 2008): policy application
  of behavioral economics findings — defaults, framing,
  choice architecture
- **Atul Gawande**, *The Checklist Manifesto* (2009):
  institutional procedures as cognitive repair —
  organizations can compensate for individual biases
- **Chip Heath et al.** (*Research in Organizational
  Behavior* 1998): "cognitive repairs" — organizational
  practices that correct for systematic individual errors

---

